{{Orphan|date=October 2016}}

{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}} {{Italic title}} 
'''''AIDS photo diary, 1986–1990''''' is an art work that comprises a photo diary that records the decline in health and eventual death of David Tosh, from [[AIDS]] from 1986 to 1990 in [[Sydney]], Australia. The diary – with accompanying photographs taken by John Jenner – was created by Jenner to remember his friend and honour the lives of people living with HIV/AIDS. Some of the images were featured in an article in ''[[Sydney Morning Herald]]''{{'}}s ''Good Weekend'' magazine, 13 October 1990, pp.&nbsp;20–29.<ref>{{cite web|title=AIDS photo diary, 1986–1990 / photographed and compiled by John Jenner|url=http://acms.sl.nsw.gov.au/item/itemdetailpaged.aspx?itemid=844424|work=SLNSW catalogue|accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref>

==Contents==
The work includes photographs by John Jenner from 1986 to 1990, together with a biography in the form of a play written by Jenner.  The diary also includes poems by Willy Barber.<ref>{{cite web|title=John Jenner – papers, 1985 – 1993|url=http://acms.sl.nsw.gov.au/item/itemDetailPaged.aspx?itemID=9514|work=SLNSW catalogue|accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref>

==Context==
This diary was one of a number of artistic responses to [[HIV/AIDS in Australia]] at a time when medications that could prolong and enhance the quality of life of those living with HIV had not been developed.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eurekastreet.com.au/articles/0310sendziuk.html |title=Denying the Grim Reaper: Australian Responses to AIDS |author=Sendziuk, Paul |work=Eureka Street |accessdate=25 December 2016}}</ref>  David Tosh died on 3 May 1990.<ref>{{cite journal|title=none|journal=Sydney Morning Herald 'Good Weekend' magazine|date=13 December 1990|page=29}}</ref>  In 1990 Australia experienced 2381 cases of AIDS as reported by the National Centre in HIV Epidemiology and Clinical Research.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Davies, Peter | author2=Aggleton, Peter | author3=Hart, Graham | title=AIDS : rights, risk, and reason | publication-date=1992 | publisher=Falmer Press | isbn=978-0-7507-0039-9 }}</ref>  97% of these cases were male and the survival rate was only 40%.

{{Quote box
 |quote  = Australia’s experience of HIV/AIDS in the 1980s and 90s is thus ancient history, and so much of that time is gone: a time of the dead and the dying; vigil shifts at ward 17; watching brilliant and beautiful men sliding into garbled dementia; polite efforts to avoid funeral scheduling conflicts; two full pages of obits in the Sydney Star Observer; anger and love and screaming horror at the waste of so many lives.
 |source = Stephen Dunne, ''[[Sydney Morning Herald]]'', 13 November 2006<ref>{{cite news|last=Dunne|first=Stephen|title=Holding the man|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/arts-reviews/holding-the-man/2006/10/26/1161749228028.html|accessdate=24 July 2013|newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald|date=13 November 2006}}</ref> 
}}

The diary was exhibited in the ''100 Objects Exhibition'' at the [[State Library of New South Wales]] in 2010.<ref>[http://www.sl.nsw.gov.au/events/exhibitions/2010/onehundred/100-objects/Exhibit-036.htm SLNSW 100 Objects Exhibition ]</ref>

