{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=August 2015}} {{Infobox organisation |name = Anthropological Survey of India |image = Indian Museum Kolkata.jpg |image_border = |size = <!-- default 200 --> |alt = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] --> |caption =The [[Indian Museum]], [[Kolkata]], the headquarters of AnSI |map = <!-- optional --> |msize = <!-- map size, optional, default 200px --> |malt = <!-- map alt text --> |mcaption = <!-- optional --> |abbreviation =AnSI |motto = |formation = 1945<!-- {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> |type = <!-- GO, NGO, IGO, INGO, etc --> |status = <!-- ad hoc, treaty, foundation, etc --> |purpose = <!-- focus as e.g. humanitarian, peacekeeping, etc --> |headquarters = [[Kolkata]] |location = |coords = <!-- Coordinates of location using a coordinates template --> |region_served = |membership = |language = <!-- official languages --> |leader_title = <!-- position title for the leader of the org --> |leader_name = <!-- name of leader --> |main_organ = <!-- gral. assembly, board of directors, etc --> |parent_organisation = [[Ministry of Culture (India)|Ministry of Culture]], [[Govt. of India]] |affiliations = <!-- if any --> |num_staff = |num_volunteers = |budget = |website = [http://www.ansi.gov.in/default.htm http://www.ansi.gov.in/default.htm] |remarks = }} '''Anthropological Survey of India''' ('''AnSI''') is the apex [[India]]n government organisation involved in [[anthropological]] studies and field data research for human and cultural aspects, working primarily in the fields of [[physical anthropology]] and [[cultural anthropology]].<ref>[http://www.education.nic.in/cd50years/12/8i/6T/8I6T0G01.htm Anthropological Survey of India] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100625023925/http://www.education.nic.in/cd50years/12/8i/6T/8I6T0G01.htm |date=25 June 2010 }} Department of Education. [[Govt. of India]].</ref> While maintaining a strong focus on [[Tribes of India|indigenous]] populations, it also attempts to document the cultures of other communities and religious groups.
==History== Anthropological Research in India was founded 1945 in [[Varanasi]] and shifted to the [[Indian Museum]] at [[Kolkata|Calcutta]] in 1948.<ref>[http://www.anthsi.com/ Anthropological Survey of India history at anthsi.com]</ref>
In 1916, the Zoological and Anthropological sections of the Museum together became a new entity the [[Zoological Survey of India]]. Later, in 1945, the Anthropology section formed into an independent body, the Anthropological Survey of India (AnSI),<ref name=an>[http://www.andaman.org/BOOK/app-k/textk.htm Anthropological Survey of India] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060525004432/http://www.andaman.org/BOOK/app-k/textk.htm |date=2006-05-25 }} (The Andamanese by George Weber).</ref> with [[Biraja Sankar Guha]] as the initial director and [[Verrier Elwin]], Deputy Director.
==Overview== {| class="toccolours" style="float: right; margin-left: 1em; font-size: 100%; background:#ffffcc; color:black; width:25em; max-width: 25%;" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" ! style="background-color:#cccccc;" | Directors |- | style="text-align: left;" | * [[Biraja Sankar Guha]], 1945-1954 * N.K. Dutta Mazumdar, 1954-1958 * [[Nirmal Kumar Bose]], 1959-1964 * D.K. Sen, 1964-1970 * [[Surajit Chandra Sinha]], 1972-1975 * [[Kumar Suresh Singh]], 1976-1977 * H.K. Rakshit, 1978-1982 * A.K. Danda, 1984-1990 * [[R.S. Mann, 1991-1992]] * [[Triloknath Pandit|T.N. Pandit]], 1992-1992 * R.K. Bhattacharya, 1993-2003 * V.R. Rao, 2003–2017 * V K Srivastava, 2017- |}
Operating under the [[Ministry of Culture (India)|Ministry of Culture]], [[Government of India]], it is headquartered in [[Kolkata]] and has branches in [[Port Blair]] ([[Andaman and Nicobar]]), [[Shillong]], [[Dehra Dun]], [[Udaipur]], [[Nagpur]] (with Central Library of AnSI), and [[Mysore]] (established in 1960),<ref>[http://www.sasnet.lu.se/asi.html Anthropological Survey of India (ASI), Mysore] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622032339/http://www.sasnet.lu.se/asi.html |date=22 June 2011 }} Swedish South Asian Studies Network, [[Lund University]], 28 November 2007.</ref> in addition to two field stations at [[Jagdalpur]] in [[Bastar district]], [[Chhattisgarh]] and at [[Ranchi]], [[Jharkhand]].{{citation needed|date=November 2011}} The Central Museum of AnSI is located at Kolkata, whereas Zonal Anthropological Museums are at six regional centres and one sub-regional centres.
