[[File:Cernuschi Museum 20060812 069.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Terra cotta]] figure from [[Shaanxi]], Western Han Period (206 BC – 9 AD)]]
'''Mingqi''' (Chinese:&nbsp;{{lang|zh|{{linktext|冥器}}}} or {{lang|zh|{{linktext|明器}}}}, <small>[[pinyin|p]]</small>&nbsp;''míngqì''), sometimes referred to as "spirit objects"<ref>Loewe, p. 266</ref> or "vessels for ghosts", are [[Religion in China|Chinese]] [[Grave goods|burial goods]]. They included daily [[Kitchen utensil|utensils]], [[musical instrument]]s, [[weapon]]s, [[armor]], and intimate objects such as the deceased's cap, can and [[bamboo]] mat.<ref name="LoeweShaughnessy1999">{{cite book|last1=Loewe|first1=Michael|last2=Shaughnessy|first2=Edward L.|title=The Cambridge history of ancient China: from the origins of civilization to 221 B.C.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cHA7Ey0-pbEC&pg=PA728http%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DcHA7Ey0-pbEC|accessdate=26 January 2011|year=1999|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-47030-8|pages=728–}}</ref> Mingqi also could include [[figurine]]s, spiritual representations rather than real people,<ref name="Higham2004">{{cite book|last=Higham|first=Charles|title=Encyclopedia of ancient Asian civilizations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H1c1UIEVH9gC&pg=PA224|accessdate=26 January 2011|year=2004|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-0-8160-4640-9|pages=224–}}</ref> of soldiers, [[servant]]s, musicians, [[polo]] riders, houses, and horses.<ref name="International1994">{{cite book|author=Rotary International|title=The Rotarian|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3TEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA23|accessdate=26 January 2011|date=January 1994|publisher=Rotary International|pages=23–|issn=0035-838X}}</ref> Extensive use of mingqi during certain periods may either have been an attempt to preserve the image of ritual propriety by cutting costs, or it may have a new idea separating the realm of the dead from that of the living.<ref name="Stark2006">{{cite book|authorlink1=Miriam Stark|last=Stark|first=Miriam T.|title=Archaeology of Asia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cCDlxPgu6LgC&pg=PA212|accessdate=26 January 2011|year=2006|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|isbn=978-1-4051-0213-1|pages=212–}}</ref>

==Purpose==
Mingqi served to provide the deceased with necessities and comforts in the afterlife. The deceased person's ''[[Hun and po|po]]'' was said to remain in the realm of the tomb while the ''hun'' ascended to heaven. To appease and make worthwhile the deceased's ''po'', mingqi claimed relevant and liked by the deceased were placed in his tomb. Upon placing mingqi in the tomb, humans, according to the Confucian ideal, were harmonizing the cosmos by striking a balance for the comfort of the deceased who is also comforted in heaven.<ref>{{cite web|last=Clydesdale|first=Heather Colburn|title=The Vibrant Role of Mingqi in Early Chinese Burials|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/toah/hd/mgqi/hd_mgqi.htm|work=Heilbrunn Timeline of Art History|publisher=The Metropolitan Museum of Art|accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref>

